{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527805"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:33:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14235"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14235"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.38,0.01,0.02,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88314"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47350"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine assessment. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, gout, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). His current medications include amlodipine 10 mg daily and perindopril 10 mg daily. On examination, he appears well with a blood pressure of 145/80 mmHg. He reports no symptoms and his recent urinalysis shows no proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate target blood pressure for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u003C120/70 mmHg","\u003C140/90 mmHg","\u003C160/100 mmHg","\u003C150/90 mmHg","\u003C130/80 mmHg"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016), blood pressure targets should be individualised through shared decision-making between patient and clinician, taking into account the potential benefits and harms of treatment, and reviewed regularly. In general, a target blood pressure of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension. In patients at high cardiovascular risk\u2014such as those with previous myocardial infarction or stroke, diabetes with microalbuminuria, moderate to severe CKD or familial hypercholesterolaemia\u2014more intensive systolic blood pressure targets (\u0026lt;120 mmHg) may be appropriate. However, such targets require careful monitoring for treatment-related adverse effects, including hypotension, syncope, electrolyte disturbances, and acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore in this patient who has type 2 diabetes but no evidence of microalbuminuria or CKD a target blood pressure of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0026lt;140/90 mHg\u003C/strong\u003E is still appropriate. Regular monitoring and adjustment of antihypertensive therapy are crucial to achieve and maintain the target blood pressure while minimising side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note the RACGP \u0022Management of type 2 diabetes\u0022 handbook also recommends a blood pressure target of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg for people with diabetes, with lower targets considered for those at high risk of stroke and with concurrent chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The target blood pressure for patients with diabetes without microalbuminuria or CKD is \u003C140/90 mmHg due to their high cardiovascular risk.","Hypertension management should be tailored to individual patient characteristics and comorbidities.","Regular blood pressure monitoring and medication adjustment are crucial in achieving target blood pressure goals."],"references":["National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Atkins ER, Perkovic V. Blood pressure: at what level is treatment worthwhile?. Aust Prescr 2019;42:127-30. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.038","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Type 2 diabetes: Goals for optimum management. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP; 2024 [cited 2025 May 24]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/management-of-type-2-diabetes/type-2-diabetes-goals-for-optimum-management","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Management of type 2 diabetes: a handbook for general practice. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP; 2020. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/7fe75f75-56e0-40e6-a433-12bd15537c5a/Management-of-type-2-diabetes-A-handbook-for-general-practice.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88314"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14235"}},"stemMedia":